And the wall collapsed …
Here's a quiz for history enthusiasts: twenty years ago, the year 1989 was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4th.
Which one do you remember best and which one had the most significant impact on the planet?
a) The bloody repression of Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) The elections in Poland
Very few respond with c).
For the events in Beijing and the death of Khomeini, which made headlines, overshadowed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarnosc in the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
Yet nothing contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe - and therefore to the re founding of the post-war international order.
There will be all sorts of commemorations of the end of communism in the coming months, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people it was a moment of glory, emblematic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory whose origins are unknown.
But having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern bloc from the beginning, one realizes that the process was long and complex.
The Polish election was a turning point, the moment when the movement for change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader in charge of Poland, General Jaruzelski, estimated that the country's economic problems were too serious for him to face alone.
Why not call on the Polish opposition, he thought - if not to find a solution - at least to share the responsibility for the situation?
After six months of bargaining, he reached a historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections, and Solidarnosc would be allowed to participate.
Communist leaders (no more than Solidarnosc) never for a moment considered that they might lose.
Even in their darkest nightmares, they imagined that they would be driven from power.
Yet that is exactly what happened.
In retrospect, it is surprising that there could have been any doubts.
Solidarnosc campaigned boldly.
A famous poster was repurposed for the occasion, that of a classic western, The Train Will Whistle Three Times, which enjoyed great success: it shows a Gary Cooper holding a ballot paper instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
On June 4th, was the day of judgment.
On that bright Sunday morning, as spring was about to give birth to summer, the voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughterhouse.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to their final perversity, which turned into an involuntary self-embarrassment.
They designed an electoral system in which Poles, instead of selecting candidates of their choice, had to strike out the names of those they did not want - in other words, all the communists listed on the ballots.
Everywhere you looked, people were getting rid of the hated autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had long awaited, the revenge on December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared martial law, banned Solidarnosc, and sent its leaders to prison.
The revolution by the pen!
Handled with style, the pen that eventually triumphs over the sword, becomes the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Some voters literally tore up their ballots, effectively decapitating the old regime with a single swift move.
Others savored the moment, perhaps lighting a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"That one put my cousin in prison," Pfft!, "Here's this apparatchik who got rich off our shortages," Pfft!
Pfft!
On the other hand, the communist campaign went almost unnoticed.
In all of Warsaw, only two government candidates bothered to put up posters.
Most relied on the monopoly they had over the media to spread their message: "Vote for Lezek, a good communist."
One can say to their credit that the regime acknowledged its defeat with remarkable grace.
The day after the elections, at three o'clock in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the party's main officials to declare: "Our defeat is total," he said, "we need to find a political solution."
This meant that he did not want violence or fraud; the communists would have to live with the election results.
Vingt years later, I am still puzzled.
Those of us covering Eastern Europe knew that Solidarnosc was going to win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would be an example for the rest of the Eastern bloc.
The election in Poland was extremely encouraging for anti-communists everywhere.
Thanks to Poland, what had seemed impossible just days earlier suddenly became achievable.
There were other signs.
In May, Hungarian reformers began to dismantle the fences erected on the border with Austria - a hole in the Iron Curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "Common European House" and rejected Brezhnev's interventionist doctrine.
Yet when the wall fell, political leaders and experts unanimously recognized: "We saw nothing coming."
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the day freedom broke out.
